doc112405: Microchip implant (animal). Microchips can be implanted by a veterinarian or at a shelter. doc112420: Microchip implant (animal). Some countries, such as Japan, require ISO-compliant microchips or a compatible reader on imported dogs and cats.[7]

doc112414: Microchip implant (animal). In dogs and cats, chips are usually inserted below the skin at the back of the neck between the shoulder blades on the dorsal midline. doc112409: Microchip implant (animal). Many veterinarians scan an animal's chip on every visit to verify correct operation. Some use the chip ID as their database index and print it on receipts, test results, vaccination certifications and other records.

doc112399: Microchip implant (animal). A microchip implant is an identifying integrated circuit placed under the skin of an animal.
